Post Description:
Visited the vaccination centre at Jalan Besar CC today with Minister @gankimyong. We will be commencing vaccinations for seniors above 70 years old from next Monday, and more vaccination centres will also be opened progressively for the convenience of all. 

Our vaccination efforts have been going well so far. About 250,000 people have received at least one dose of the vaccine. We are now getting supplies from both Pfizer and Moderna. Based on the expected supply schedule, another 1 million people should be able to get at least one dose of the vaccine by around end-March/early-April. This will cover all seniors above 60. 

Do encourage your seniors at home to get vaccinated when their turn comes, for their protection and safety.

Post Description:
Good news! We received our first shipment of Moderna vaccines this afternoon. This follows another batch of Pfizer-BioNTech vaccines that arrived this morning. These shipments will enable us to progressively roll out our vaccination programme, with vaccination for seniors in the community set to begin later next week.
 
We expect more vaccines from both Moderna and Pfizer-BioNTech to arrive over the coming months. We will continue to monitor our supplies closely, to meet our target of vaccinating all Singaporeans and long-term residents by the end of this year.

Post Description:
Got my Covid-19 vaccination today together with @gankimyong while visiting Kwong Wai Shiu hospital. Both Kim Yong and I have been encouraging everyone to get vaccinated. So we felt we should do so early ourselves, to assure Singaporeans that we have full confidence in the safety and effectiveness of the vaccine.

I just took a flu jab last year. The process for the Covid vaccine is very similar. It was a painless and seamless procedure, and I didn‚Äôt feel any side effects, other than mild soreness in the arm. 

We are steadily ramping up our nationwide Covid vaccine programme. For now, the priority is to vaccinate healthcare and frontline workers, including those working at our border entry checkpoints like our air and sea port workers. Later this month, we will start the vaccination for seniors.  When your turn comes, do take up the vaccine to protect yourself and your loved ones.

Post Description:
As we roll out our Covid-19 vaccination programme, starting with healthcare workers and frontliners, people naturally have concerns over the safety and efficacy of the vaccine. 

Was invited to a special episode of Talking Point to address these issues, alongside healthcare experts Assoc Prof Benjamin Ong and Assoc Prof Vernon Lee. I hope that through our assurance and explanations, you will have confidence to take up the vaccine when it is available to you, to protect yourselves and your loved ones from the virus. 

Catch the episode tomorrow, 7 Jan, on Channel 5 at 9.30pm.

Post Description:
Our Bedok Community Centre COVID-19 vaccination centre will be starting operations from Monday, 8 March.¬†

Seniors aged 70 and above will be progressively receiving personalised letters inviting them to make an appointment for their vaccinations. Those who have received their invitations letters can register for vaccination at www.vaccine.gov.sg. For those who have yet to receive your invitations, I seek your patience to wait for your turn.

Community volunteers and care ambassadors and resident volunteers have been going door-to-door to help our seniors make their vaccinations appointments and answer their queries. A big thank you to all our volunteers and @pafrenz for organising this outreach effort. I also thank the healthcare professionals, who will be carrying out the vaccinations.¬†

Do help our seniors get vaccinated, and I encourage you to do so when you are offered. By getting vaccinated, you are protecting not only yourself, but also your loved ones.

#EastCoastCares
Comments: Very Good! The vaccination is starting at Bedok.

Post Description:
Got the second dose of my COVID-19 vaccination at the National Centre for Infectious Diseases this morning. Much like the first time, it was fast and painless, and I was monitored for 30 minutes afterwards. Other than a slight soreness in my arm, I feel perfectly fine!

During my walkabouts, many residents asked about our national vaccination programme. Some also wanted to hear about my personal experience. I assured them that vaccination is safe and effective. We will be progressively setting up more community vaccination centres in the heartlands, including in Bedok, prioritising seniors and those at greater risk of infection. I hope that you will take the vaccine when it is offered to you ‚Äî to protect not just yourself, but your loved ones as well.

(PMO Video by Arina Ong)
Comments: Why is she not wearing any gloves when doing the injection?

We will be progressively setting up more community vaccination centres in the heartlands, including in Bedok, prioritising seniors and those at greater risk of infection. I hope that you will take the vaccine when it is offered to you ‚Äî to protect not just yourself, but your loved ones as well.

(PMO Video by Arina Ong)
Comments: Yellow is Tampines Central colour.‚ù§Ô∏è

Post Description:
Took my first dose of the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccination this morning at the National Centre of Infectious Diseases, @tantocksenghospital. Post Description:
The global scientific community has played a critical role in the fight against COVID-19, from the development of diagnostic tests and vaccines, to innovations to help all of us adapt to the crisis. Their continued research and innovations will be crucial in helping us overcome the pandemic and build back better from this crisis.‚Å£
‚Å£
Their individual efforts of scientists and researchers are greatly multiplied by working together. This is what we seek to do in Singapore ‚Äî by strengthening global partnerships with partners from around the world. The Global Young Scientists Summit is an annual event we organised to do just that.‚Å£
‚Å£
I kicked off the 9th edition of the Summit this morning. Glad to have brought together 500 young scientists and researchers from 30 countries. We also welcome more than twenty distinguished speakers and panellists ‚Äî who count among them Noble laureates, Fields medallists, Turing Award and Millennium Technology prize winners.‚Å£
‚Å£
I hope the young scientists will be inspired to further pursue their passion for science and technology and to push the frontiers of innovation. And I welcome our overseas participants to visit Singapore when air travel resumes.‚Å£
‚Å£
By working together, we can rebuild from this crisis, and create a better and brighter future for the world.‚Å£
‚Å£
#GYSS2021‚Å£
#ScientistsinSG
Comments: Good to promote Young Scientists.

Post Description:
Today is the first day back at school for many students. For parents of Primary 1 students, I hope that your child is adapting to the school routine. 
 
It is also the first week of work for adults, including for Parliament. As I walked to Parliament House yesterday, the streets were noticeably busier as offices in the CBD resumed activities.
 
At Parliament yesterday, @gankimyong shared that more vaccine shipments are expected and there will be enough vaccines for all Singaporeans, PRs  and long-term residents by 3Q of 2021 if all goes to plan. @lawrencewongst explained how regular testing will be ramped up and will become a part of our lives during the pandemic.
 
This is how we started the year ‚Äî with a dose of hope and a note of vigilance. And this is how we should approach the year ahead.
 
I wish everyone a happy start to the first week of 2021!
Comments: Happy New Year! A Good Year Ahead!

Post Description:
We started our national COVID-19 vaccination programme today. 

Our healthcare workers at the National Centre for Infectious Diseases were the first to receive the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine in Singapore. They will get their second dose in 21 days. We will progressively roll out our vaccination program to staff at public healthcare institutions and private hospitals. We aim to make vaccination available to the elderly from February next year.

This comes after the Government accepted all the recommendations of the Expert Committee on COVID-19 Vaccinations on Sunday. The vaccine will enable us to better protect ourselves and our loved ones. 

Let me take this opportunity to thank all our healthcare workers and frontline staff for your dedication and outstanding work in keeping all of us safe in Singapore.

(Senior staff nurse Sarah Lim was the first to receive the Pfizer BioNTech vaccine this morning. / MCI Photo by Lee Jia Wen)
Comments: üôèüèª deep appreciation for the vaccination rollout

Post Description:
The @unitednations is marking its 75th anniversary in an extraordinary year.
 
Every country is doing its best to contain the spread of the virus and the economic fallout. But no place can truly be safe, until every place is safe.
 
This is why strong international cooperation is critical to accelerate the development of vaccines, maximise production capacity, and ensure the affordable, fair and equitable access to vaccines for all.
 
New and innovative forms of multilateral cooperation have been created in response to the pandemic, including the Access to COVID-19 Tools (ACT) Accelerator and the COVID-19 Global Vaccines Access (COVAX) Facility. Singapore is an early support of these initiatives, and also co-chairs the Friends of the COVAX Facility with Switzerland.
 
Our collective effort will enable us to overcome this crisis. By working together and strengthening the foundations of international cooperation, we can better deal with future crises and achieve the Sustainable Development Goals, so as to build a better future for our people. 
 
You can watch my recorded statement at the High-Level Event on the COVID-19 response at the UN General Assembly on my Facebook Page. 

(MCI Photo by Zinkie Aw)
Comments: I still dk the east coast plan

Post Description:
Health and finance have always been closely intertwined, and in a pandemic, this is even more so. Earlier this evening, Gan Kim Yong and I participated in the Joint Finance and Health Ministers Meeting hosted by @g20org. We thank our Saudi colleagues for their leadership. COVID-19 is a global crisis, so international cooperation is critical. The #G20, which covers nearly 80% of the world‚Äôs economy, and the @who have key roles to play.
 
Countries, International Organisations and the private sector are joining forces to accelerate vaccine development, maximise manufacturing capacity, and ensure equitable distribution. Singapore is an early supporter of the COVID-19 Vaccine Global Access Facility. Switzerland and Singapore are also co-chairing the ‚ÄúFriends of the COVAX Facility‚Äù to promote vaccine multilateralism. 
 
At the same time, as we restart our economies in a safe manner, countries need to coordinate our resumption of activities. As we restart air travel, testing will be key to give assurance to travellers and public health authorities. We must work together to develop international standards, and share test results quickly including through electronic means.
 
We must also continue to identify gaps and strengthen our health and financial resilience against future outbreaks.
 
(MCI Photo by Betty Chua)
Comments: ‚ù§Ô∏èthis is a good initiative. thank u DPM for such efforts. agree totally with u

Post Description:
I spoke to PRC Vice Premier Han Zheng earlier today. Much has changed since we last spoke in February, as we now face the common challenge of resuming social and economic activities, while safeguarding against further waves of COVID-19 infections.‚Å£
‚Å£
Vice Premier Han and I discussed how China and Singapore can deepen existing cooperation and work together in new areas. One key area of cooperation that we discussed was public health, including the development of COVID-19 diagnostics, vaccines and treatments. I thanked Vice Premier Han for China‚Äôs pledge to make Chinese vaccines available globally. We also agreed that it was important to further strengthen connectivity between our two countries and with the rest of the world, in areas such as supply chain, financial, infrastructure and flight connectivity. This will enable the flow of goods, people and investments that are necessary for economic recovery.‚Å£
‚Å£
I am glad that our joint efforts to create new opportunities and enhance connectivity have continued despite COVID-19, including through key bilateral projects and cooperation on the Belt and Road Initiative. The strides that we have taken reflects our common resolve to overcome the pandemic together and emerge stronger.‚Å£
‚Å£
This is an important year for our countries as we mark the 30th anniversary of diplomatic relations. I look forward to welcoming Vice Premier Han to Singapore for the Joint Council for Bilateral Cooperation (JCBC) meeting when the COVID situation permits.‚Å£
‚Å£
(With PRC Vice Premier Han Zheng at the opening of China-Singapore Chongqing Connectivity Initiative Gallery, in October 2019. / MCI Photo by Chwee)
Comments: Boycott Chinese Products! Down with the CCP!

Post Description:
I could not hold my annual Chap Goh Mei dinner with community leaders and other guests this year because of COVID-19. Instead, I spoke to a small audience at NTUC Auditorium, while groups joined us from 126 other locations virtually.

I took stock of our COVID-19 situation. We want to maintain our current stable position and get Singaporeans vaccinated quickly. The vaccines will take us one big step forward, but not back to business as usual, as many countries will not complete their vaccinations within this year. We have to live with the virus for many more years to come, maybe even permanently.

I also shared my thoughts on our external situation, and the outlook for the future. The next few years will not be easy. We can‚Äôt tell exactly how the world will change after the pandemic, but as long as we work together, hold fast to our principles, and keep faith both with our pioneers as well as generations yet unborn, we will emerge stronger and thrive for many years to come. ‚Äì LHL
 
(MCI Photo by Chwee)
Comments: Very nice daddy lee hsien loong

Post Description:
We began vaccinating seniors 70 and above in Ang Mo Kio and Tanjong Pagar today. These two estates have older residents than most other estates.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I dropped by Ang Mo Kio Polyclinic this morning to see how the pilot exercise was going. Pleased to see a good turn out today!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
The vaccination programme will be rolled out to other estates from mid-February. If you have seniors at home who have received the letter, please help them make their appointment for their vaccination. I encourage everyone to get vaccinated as soon as you can. The more of us are protected, the sooner we can get back to a more normal life. ‚Äì LHL

Post Description:
Was at Singapore General Hospital (@sghseen) this morning to take a look at the start of COVID-19 vaccinations for healthcare workers from public institutions today. I also got my first dose of the jab!

It was quite painless, with the tiny needle and the steady hands of Senior Staff Nurse Fatimah Mohd Shah. I was observed for 30 minutes after getting the vaccine but I am happy to report that I feel fine and have no side effects.

I am confident that the vaccine is safe and effective. We will have ample vaccines for everyone, so I hope Singaporeans and long-term residents will get vaccinated when your turn comes, and help keep everyone safer. ‚Äì LHL

([1,2,4,5] MCI Photo by Fyrol; [3] Photo by me)

Post Description:
Got my first dose of the COVID-19 vaccine today, together with Director of Medical Services A/Prof Kenneth Mak. We got vaccinated early to show Singaporeans we are confident that the vaccine is safe and effective.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Prof Mak and I were monitored for 30 minutes after the jab, just in case we developed any side effects, e.g. allergic reactions. Happy to report that we both felt fine.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Today we started vaccinating healthcare workers from public healthcare institutions. We aim to start vaccinating elderly people from February, and then other Singaporeans and long-term residents.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Vaccinations are voluntary, but I hope that when it‚Äôs your turn, you will go for it. It will be free, it will protect you and your family, and it will help keep everyone safe. ‚Äì LHL
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
(PMO Video by Alex Qiu)‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

Post Description:
Today we began COVID-19 vaccinations, with 30+ healthcare workers at the National Centre for Infectious Diseases. It marks a new chapter in our fight against the pandemic. 
 
In the coming weeks, the vaccine will be rolled out to more healthcare institutions. We will begin vaccinating the elderly from February. Thereafter we will do other Singaporeans and long-term residents who are eligible for vaccination.
 
The vaccine is key to living in a COVID-19 world, but it will still be some time before this storm will pass. Meanwhile, let‚Äôs stay vigilant to keep ourselves and our loved ones healthy and safe. ‚Äì LHL

Post Description:
It has been a long year. But because of our collective efforts against COVID-19, we are ready to ease into Phase 3 on 28 December. This is possible because of all of you who made many sacrifices, so that our numbers and situation are now under control.

We will also provide free, voluntary vaccines for all Singaporeans and long-term residents. We have approved the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine for use, and the first batch will arrive by the end of 2020. We are still looking at other candidates, and by 3Q2021, we should have enough vaccines for everyone. 

I encourage that you get vaccinated, because you are not just protecting yourself, but people around you. This announcement will bring some year-end cheer to you and your friends and family, but we must maintain our vigilance as the virus is not yet eradicated. It might be a year or more before we are in the clear, but at least we can see light at the end of the tunnel. ‚Äì LHL

(MCI Photo by Chwee)

We will also provide free, voluntary vaccines for all Singaporeans and long-term residents. We have approved the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine for use, and the first batch will arrive by the end of 2020. We are still looking at other candidates, and by 3Q2021, we should have enough vaccines for everyone. 

I encourage that you get vaccinated, because you are not just protecting yourself, but people around you. This announcement will bring some year-end cheer to you and your friends and family, but we must maintain our vigilance as the virus is not yet eradicated. It might be a year or more before we are in the clear, but at least we can see light at the end of the tunnel. ‚Äì LHL

(MCI Photo by Chwee)
Comments: hi pm Lee I love your smile üòÉ

Post Description:
We officially started the Sea-Air Vaccination Exercise for our frontliners working at our borders on 18 Jan 2021. 

The attached graph shows the progress made in the maritime sector. 

The top horizontal line shows the number of frontline workers eligible - 18k. 

The first line bordering the blue area shows the number that got their first dose over the last 1.5 months. The number now stands at 17.6k, or 98% of eligible frontline maritime personnel. 

The second line bordering the green area shows the number who have received the second dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. 16.7k have, and in the coming days, almost all would have. 

This means that substantially all frontline maritime workers will be vaccinated, and this is a major step in securing our borders and minimising import cases infiltrating our community, and strengthening international confidence in our maritime hub. 

I thank the various stakeholders - @maritime_sg, EDB, EnterpriseSG, SMOU, SOS, SSA, ASMI, @moh_singapore, Fullerton Health, maritime companies, and also workers and their families, for their tremendous support. 

#MaritimeSGSteadyLah
#MaritimeSG
Comments: ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è Well done! Thank you for protecting our frontline specialists.

Post Description:
My fellow Sembawang GRC MPs spoke in Parliament during the Budget Debate over the last two days.

Dr Lim Wee Kiak called for the rebate package for taxi and private hire drivers to be brought forward, which Government has followed up on.

Ms Mariam explained why when evaluating Singapore√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s carbon emission, we need to take into account of the fact that Singapore is a city state which provides aviation, maritime and chemical processing services to the rest of the world.

Ms Poh Li San spoke about how Singapore, despite its limitations, has set a good international example on sustainability and conservation.

Mr Vikram Nair had useful suggestions on how to encourage more people to receive Covid-19 vaccinations.

Thank you to the voices of Sembawang MPs! #MakeSembawangSpecial

Post Description:
Mr Tham, 72, was one of the first taxi drivers to get vaccinated today. 

More than 50,000 active taxi and private hire car drivers will receive an SMS this week to book their vaccination slot. 

Amongst the more than 12,000 taxi and PHC drivers who went for voluntary swab test last September, none tested positive. This is partly due to all the safe measures that have been put in place. 

Notwithstanding, vaccination is an important added protection for our drivers, their families and commuters. 

Thank you to the drivers for stepping forward and setting aside time to get your vaccinations.

Stay well and drive safe!
Comments: A little jab will surely make cabbies drive a longer way.

Post Description:
Today, we start the Sea-Air #Vaccination Exercise, to vaccinate 37,000 frontliners of the #aviation and #maritime industry. 

They are our airplane and port pilots, cabin crew, cargo handlers, transit lounge workers, local seafarers, ship and plane repair technicians etc. 

Some 13,000 of them have registered to be vaccinated this week, and hopefully more will do so in the coming weeks as we step up the capacity of the two vaccination centres at @changiairport T4 and Raffles City to 8,000 a day. 

We aim to substantially complete the exercise within two months. 

These 37,000 workers come into contact with people and cargo from outside #Singapore. When vaccinated, they will not just protect themselves and their families, but they would have taken a big step to secure the borders of Singapore and keep us safe from COVID-19.

#OneAviation #MaritimeSG
Comments: Minister Ong, what about our MRT customer service guys that are always on rhe Station platforms and bus captains. When will they be vaccinated.

Post Description:
We start vaccination for the #aviation and #maritime sectors this afternoon, at two centres: @changiairport T4 for air crew and frontline airport workers, and Raffles City Convention Centre for marine pilots, crew and frontline workers who have to go onboard ships.

This week will be an operational warm-up, where we will vaccinate small groups, to prepare for full scale operations next week. 

I will be at T4 with the CEOs of key aviation companies next Monday to explain the significance of this exercise.
Comments: Big thanks for the effort!

Post Description:
A historic cold chain moment on the night of Winter Solstice Festival (√•‚Ä†¬¨√®‚Ä°¬≥). The first vaccine shipment has finally arrived, safely and smoothly.

It reached our tarmac from Brussels this evening, on a @singaporeair cargo plane. From flight to delivery, a lot of preparation has gone into making this as smooth as possible, including a trial flight by #SIA.

Changi air hub ecosystem has been working out the processes for months, with a specially set up Taskforce. One of the challenges they identified was to ensure sufficient supply of dry ice. So #SATS is now producing 4 tonnes of dry ice per day, on its own facility!

The real work starts now.
Comments: Big appreciation to all involved!

It reached our tarmac from Brussels this evening, on a @singaporeair cargo plane. From flight to delivery, a lot of preparation has gone into making this as smooth as possible, including a trial flight by #SIA.

Changi air hub ecosystem has been working out the processes for months, with a specially set up Taskforce. One of the challenges they identified was to ensure sufficient supply of dry ice. So #SATS is now producing 4 tonnes of dry ice per day, on its own facility!

The real work starts now.

Post Description:
Today, I dropped by the monthly job fair at Kampung Admiralty with @pohlisan. The job fair is supported by NTUC e2i.

Out of more than 2,700 immediate job vacancies by 80 employers at the fair, 2,300 jobs are located in and around Sembawang GRC. Our volunteers have been calling on local enterprises to gather these job vacancies. 

Job Stations at the fair, available in the four official languages, can also help residents by highlighting jobs within the 5km radius. And companies present at the fair will interview interested applicants on the spot. 

This has been a difficult period for residents whose jobs are affected by COVID-19. I hope the job fair will help.

#MakeSembawangSpecial @ilovee2i
Comments: If is not good is aready the best done we can ask for more

Post Description:
This is the √¢‚Ç¨≈ìhealth certificate√¢‚Ç¨¬ù that may come in handy when you travel next time.

COVID-19 test results, and soon, your vaccination status, may become very relevant information at the check-in and immigration counters for cross border travel. But they will need to be easily verifiable.

Airlines are foreseeing this. So @singaporeair is working with International Air Transport Association (#IATA), and #Affinidi, a local technology company founded by @temasekseen, to start a trial on digital verification for COVID-19 tests and soon, vaccinations.

Accredited labs will issue a health certificate - a QR code on mobile or printed on paper - to passengers, to be scanned and verified easily and securely by airlines and immigration officers using an app.

Hopefully, with the support of IATA, various airlines and authorities around the world, this can become the norm, and replace the yellow book.

I applaud the industry√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s initiative. @motsingapore and #CAAS will support this as much as we can, to make this a regional or international practice. We are #OneAviation team. 

Photo credit: Affinidi
[The verifier app developed by Affinidi (foreground) lets airline staff and ICA officials easily scan QR codes to verify COVID-19 test results. The QR code in the background is stored on a separate app developed by International SOS.]
Comments: This is really soooo amazing. Feeling very blessed that we're so organised and systematic in the way we do things. Kudos to the people who did all the planning with so much thought and foresight.

Post Description:
Phase 3 announced, vaccines in transit. Steps will also be taken, to allow limited, safe, face-to-face international business meetings.

Zoom cannot replace some face-to-face business meetings, e.g. signing agreements, or discussing with key teams, getting to know key partners in person.

Connect@Changi, will provide the first of its kind facility to enable such meetings to be carried out safely.

This is a national resilience project, led by @temasekseen, @surbanajurong, @changiairport, Ascott and SingEx.

This video explains how it is done.

Post Description:
üíâü¶†vaccinations, let‚Äôs go.
 
today, senior staff nurse sarah lim became the first person in singapore to receive a covid-19 vaccination, with more than 30 other healthcare workers at the national centre for infectious diseases also set to receive the jab.

they are getting their first dose of the covid-19 vaccine developed by united states pharmaceutical giant pfizer and german firm biontech. this vaccine requires two injections, given 21 days apart. those who receive the first dose today (dec 30) are scheduled to return for their second dose on jan 20 next year.

watch the video, and read our story when you click on the link in bio @todayonline

Post Description:
singapore is the first asian country to receive the vaccine. 

singapore received its first shipment of covid-19 vaccine yesterday evening on board a singapore airlines (sia) cargo flight from belgium, where it was manufactured.

the pfizer-biontech vaccine arrived at changi airport at about 7.35pm.

the vaccine for the sars-cov-2 coronavirus is the first one to be approved for use in singapore. vaccines produced by other drug manufacturers are expected to arrive in singapore in the coming months.

in a facebook post yesterday night, prime minister lee hsien loong said that the governmental covid-19 task force will announce the details of the roll-out of the vaccination schedules in due course. "we are prioritising our healthcare workers and the elderly. vaccination will be voluntary, but i encourage singaporeans to take the vaccine," he said.

Post Description:
üõ¨ the first shipment of covid-19 vaccines arrived in singapore on 21 december.

the pfizer-biontech covid-19 vaccine was transported on singapore airlines flight sq7979, which departed on sunday 20 december from brussels, and landed at singapore changi airport at 7.36pm on monday.

the vaccines were packed in thermal shipper boxes filled with dry ice designed to keep the vials at -70 degree celsius.

upon arrival, ground handler sats moved the vaccines to its cold chain facility. they were then loaded onto a refrigerated truck that would send them to an external storage facility with capabilities to handle ultra-cold storage at about -80 degree celsius.

staff and logistics partners have been trained up to who standards to be able to handle the cargo safely.

for more information on how singapore secured access to the vaccines, go to go.gov.sg/vaccinearrival-sg-ig (link in bio)

photos: ministry of communications and information (mci)
Comments: Amazing care shown towards Singaporeans. Filled with immense gratitude. Proud & blessed Singaporean.üôèüá∏üá¨üá∏üá¨
